<br>
She gathered a few trinkets of magickal power and checked over her inventory of weapons. The bone dirk, with a ragged edge that tore at her prey's muscles and crippled them, secure at her hip. No time for the Rapier, it took to much room to use properly anyway. She opted for her bloodclaw stiletto as a second weapon. Small enough to use in tight spaces, and easy to conceal, she placed it grip-down at the small of her back. She quickly shrugged into the remainder of her ravenscale armor, black as the darkest night. Passing a servant as she left through the front door, she handed him a small note. Instructions would need to be carried out should she not return to her household.<br>
<br>
As she made her way through the city, her thoughts drifted to Dantrazz. How she loved that man...She hoped that he was faring well on his ocean voyage, but she sensed something else was afoot apart from his natural curiosity of the new lands. There would be time to look into that later. For now, Xosha's life hung in the balance.<br>
<br>
She approached the hall of the Ebon Mask and passed around and to the right of the statues flanking its main entrance. Pressing a tiny depression in the rock wall, she made a series of movements too quick for a normal eye to see. A burst of mystikal energies sparked away from the wall and suddenly a passage was open. Morrigu strode into the tunnel and did not even wait to see it close up again behind her. She padded softly down the corridor, familiar with the twists and turn even though it had been many seasons since she had used this old entrance.<br>
<br>
Arriving atthe central chamber deep below she saw very nearly what she had expected, which meant that her informant had been telling her the truth. She was glad that some within the Ebon Mask remembered the old ways of honor among rogues. Xosha was sitting in an ornately carved chair, lashed to it by leather straps. She had obviously struggled when they had come for her, he skin was marred in several plaves by cuts and bruises, now turning a livid purple. A device had been placed into her mouth that resembled a small fruit. Morrigu well know it's origin and function, she had used it on spies many times before. Known as &quot;the Plum&quot; it was a mechanical contrivance that was the apporximate size and shap of the fruit for which it had been named, but was segmented into three equal parts length-wise. At the turn of a screw the three parts would seperate further and further from one another until the whole of the expanded device filled the person's mouth completely, preventing them from speaking at all. If opened all the way the device was easily capable of breaking a person's jaw in several places.<br>
<br>
Tani N'Mar sat silently at an ornate altar, wearing the eyeless hood of the judicator. Morrigu would know the man's form anywhere, even silent and still as he was now. He had been her guildmaster for far too long for her not to know him. Molon stood wearing the ornate traditional mask of Righteous Accusation, making his argument clear before the board of officers of the Jindurn d'Xola or Ebon Mask. <br>
<br>
Morrigu noticed that no one there carried the symbolic Shield of the Defender. Normally at a council trial the accused had the option of speaking for their own defense, but Morrigu knew that gagged as she was Xosha would not be able to utter more than a croak or a rasped cough. To her credit she sat in silent defiance, not giving the council the satisfaction of enjoying her maltreatment. Morrigu then noticed that the shield (a tiny gold jewel-encrusted flimsy thing) was at Xosha's feet, resting against her bound legs. So they were indeed going to sentance her to death, and she was not to be given the chance to defend herself at all. Morrigu gnashed her teeth in silent rage and slipped into the shadows, breathing a single Word of power as she began to move to the front of the room unnoticed by the &quot;best&quot; thieves and cutthroats of Neriak.<br>
<br>
&quot;So you can easily see, Gentlemen and Ladies of the Council,&quot; Molon spoke from behind his mask &quot;that this woman, this ingrate, had continuously defied our authority. She even went so far as to KILL two of our long-standing members without a commission on their heads! In closing, I humbly ask of the council and the Judicator that we sentance this piece of trash to death. Death is what she has earned!&quot;<br>
<br>
A sporadic applause ran through the gathered officers.<br>
<br>
&quot;Does the accused or a member of her defense have any rebuttal?&quot; Tani intoned from behind the eyeless hood.<br>
<br>
Silence dominated the courtroom.<br>
<br>
&quot;All right then, if..&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I believe that there are a few things to be said.&quot; Morrigu spoke, stepping from the shadows and lifting the Shield of the Defender to rest on her left arm.<br>
<br>
Shocked gasps and angry mutters ran throughout the courtroom. Morrigu could swear that beneath the hood Tani N'Mar was breaking a grin.<br>
<br>
&quot;YOU!&quot; Molon cried, &quot;You witch, defiler of our ways, you have no place in this court!&quot;<br>
<br>
Morrigu calmly regarded Molon T'Plith, standing in a relaxed posture and holding her head erect and proud. &quot;Hello, Molon....still enjoying my old job? I WILL speak for the girl, since you seem so eager for her not to speak at all. Does this trouble you? I know the procedures of this court and of the Mask. Am I not still a member of this council, though I have chosen to tend to other business these many years?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I object! I object most strenuously! Lord Judicator, she seeks to make a mockery of our tradition, of these very preceedings, and of yourself, M'Lord!&quot; Molon nearly screamed in his impotent rage.<br>
<br>
&quot;And do you object strongly enough to decide it with Thalra l'sargh d'Vlos, the blood-struggle?&quot; Morrigu raised her eyebrow and looked directly at Molon. When he eventually averted his gaze to the floor she scanned the room to see if any others wanted to speak out. No one met her gaze or even cleared their throats.<br>
<br>
The Judicator spoke. &quot;I believe I will know when anyone in this room attempts to make a mockery of me. Do you yourself have that sense, Lord Accuser? Lady W'Rath has had a distiguished career as one of our most accomplished assassins before she left our service. I think she may continue in her defense of this woman.&quot; He motioned for Morrigu to carry on.<br>
<br>
Morrigu stood tall as she addressed the courtroom. &quot;I have no love of this excessive protocal, so I will be brief. The charges may or may not be true, I care not. The punishment may or may not fit the crimes, again, I care not. We all know that this court has been convened today for purely political reasons.&quot;<br>
<br>
A few nods broke through the court, mostly from those who had not applauded at Molon's closing accusations.<br>
<br>
&quot;Our traditions carry few rules as hard and fast, never meant to be broken. One of these is the Right of Apprenticeship. Molon, be a dear and recite this Right?&quot;<br>
<br>
Molon's body shook in helpless rage, but from behind the mask a voice intoned &quot;Any officer of long-standing within the Ebon Mask may take upon themselves an apprentice from within the ranks of our cadets. This apprentice shall be treated with the same regard as the Officer themself, and any wrongdoings of either shall fall upon the head of both. No harm shall come to the Apprentice save that the Officer shall pay equally.&quot;<br>
<br>
Morrigu nodded her head. &quot;Very good, Molon, I see that SOME good has come of that dagger's hilt rammed up your ass... I have been long without an apprentice. Many of you remember the mad Xandriel, and the gap between then and now has left me...lonely. I have chosen Xosha as my apprentice, and I will be responsible for her education from her on out. She is now under my allegiance and protection. Now, who among you feel like putting ME in that chair?&quot; Morrigu casually pointed to Xosha where she sat.<br>
<br>
Again, silence dominated the courtroom. Molon T'Plith shook like the dog he was in place, but did not utter a sound. Morrigu set down the Shield of the Defender upon the altar and strode over to the chair where Xosha still sat bound.<br>
<br>
&quot;I thought not. And now, Lords and Ladies of the Mask, we take our leave of you. Goodbye.&quot;<br>
<br>
Morrigu casually cut the cords holding Xosha and gingerly assisted her to her feet. Unable to stand due to the lack of blood in her legs, Xosha nealy collapsed before Morrigu lifted her like a kitten into her arms and walked quietly out of the room. The gathered members of the Mask let out a collective sigh or relief, for bloodshed on a large scale had been narrowly averted. Not a single one of them had wanted to be on the business end of Morrigu's blades. None of them, of course, save one.<br>
<br>
&quot;This court stands adjourned!&quot; Tani said as he removed his hood. &quot;Molon, old boy, I think you grow smarter in your middle age...when Morrigu held your job you were constantly testing her. I think you avoided death today by holding your tongue, yes?&quot; Tani chuckled as he left the room.<br>
<br>
Molon T'Plith let the mask fall from his face and to the floor, striking with a dull thud. He was the last person in the room and he stared directly at the wall and spoke to no one in particular.<br>
<br>
