<br>
&quot;Again!&quot; Screamed Morrigu the Redhand. &quot;All wrong! Dammit Xosha what the hell do I have to tell you to get you to understand? It's Right-Dodge-Left-Parry-Insert below the thigh-Cut upwards!&quot; <br>
<br>
Xosha, newly appointed apprentice to Master Redhand nodded, and clenched her nouth in concentration. The sharp bars that were Morrigu's comments stung her when they had started Xosha's apprenticeship, two weeks ago, but now, Xosha heard in them the ring of truth, and the power that could be achieved if headed. So she did. Xosha listened when belittled for she knew that Morrigu was right, she was doing it wrong. <br>
<br>
They were sparring in the arena of Qeynos of all places. The journey had been a strange and long one from the halls of High Keep, where the Tier'Dal race was sometimes tolerated, but never liked. Here they had met after Morrigu had told her that her apprenticeship had begun. Xosha was in the bar when they had met, drinking slowly as she always did, and looking at the door. She wanted to make sure Morrigu didn't slip past her, for to be caught on awares was the very death of an assassin, that atleast Xosha knew first hand. <br>
<br>
She was so eager to see her teacher enter that when the touch at her shoulder came she jumped like a cowardly puppy. Then without thinking she drew her blade and spun. Her spin was met by a hard striking to the face, and next thing Xosha knew she was face first on the wooden flooring of that High Hold bar with Morrigu looking down at her. &quot;Wrong child, all wrong...&quot; <br>
<br>
Later, they had started thier journey into Qeynos, when Xosha was at last able to use her mouth again. &quot;Master Redhand, why Qeynos? Is it not the city of dogs? I have heard nothing of it's importance to the...&quot; Xosha was silenced by a chill look from Morrigu. <br>
<br>
&quot;I WAS going to tell you, now I think I'd rather YOU tell me, and if you are wrong, I'll leave you in Qeynos to find your answers yourself.&quot; Morrigu replied contritely. <br>
<br>
This time Xosha held her tongue and nodded. <br>
<br>
It was a moment later that a young wood elf crossed thier paths. A pretty thing she was, full of innocence and stupidity and love. Xosha drew her weapons immediately. She faced the Fier'Dal with hate in her eyes and Innoruuk's prayers on her lips. <br>
<br>
Morrigu turned to Xosha instantly, cuffed her behind the head, and then turned to the treehugger. &quot;Spare a spirit of the wolf for my traveling companion and I?&quot; asked the Matroness. <br>
<br>
The treehugger was doubtful at first, obviously her elders had told her of the evils of the true race, but her ignorance and her disgusting love won over eventually and she smiled and began her casting. <br>
<br>
A minute later the wood elf was off, Xosha watched her go in confusion. <br>
<br>
&quot;Master Redhand...&quot; Xosha stopped herself, almost unsure of whether to ask. <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes apprentice?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Master, excuse my impudence, but may I ask of thee a humble question?&quot; Xosha bowed her head as she spoke. <br>
<br>
&quot;Better. Your answer is this. The effects of this spell last many hours and we have much land to cover to get to Qeynos. We are assassins and our ways are those of deception, not of quick spirited earthy worship. We use the Fier'Dal by playing on her weakness, in this case, her love, and we gain from it.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes master.&quot; <br>
<br>
In a half hour Morrigu turned a ways from thier path into a small copse of woods with a stream flowing through it. A soft humming could be heard inside. Before her curious student could even ask Morrigu shushed her and motioned for her to follow, keeping to the shadows and watching to not step on twigs or anything that would reveal thier location. At the bank of the stream was the pretty Fier'Dal druid, washing her tunic in the water and singing some damned song to Tunare. Morrigu slowly crept to her, on all fours, with her bone dirk in her mouth. When she was near enough to touch the elf she rose to her feet, and tapped the Fier'Dal on the shoulder. The woman turned to see a dirk in her stomach. When she died she had such a look of confusion and fear of death. <br>
<br>
Later, in that same grove Xosha ventured into a dangerous territory and asked. &quot;But master, the wood elf was out of our way, we have wasted time in tracking her. Why this killing?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Child you have very much to learn. Would Innoruuk have forgiven me for allowing such a good deed as that one did for us to go unpunished? We have now gained in two ways, our trip was sped by the spell, and our master was praised by her death.&quot; Xosha smiled... <br>
<br>
&quot;Will you show me that trick that you did to her Master?&quot; <br>
<br>
Morrigu grinned widely. &quot;Yes, in the arena, in Qeynos. There is much for you to learn. To be MY apprentice you will need to kill. And you will need to kill like an assassin. You fight like a barbarian warrior, it is sick. But now, now I think maybe you are ready for my lessons.&quot; <br>
<br>
The two linked arms and sped thier wolf spirited feet towards the land of dogs and cowards, to Qeynos. <br>
<br>
